==Relation to other scripts==
;Similarities
Sinhala is one of the [[Brahmic family|Brahmic scripts]], and thus shares many similarities with other members of the family, such as the [[Kannada]], [[Malayalam]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Tamil script]] and [[DevanƒÅgarƒ´]]. As a general example, {{IPA|/a/}} is the inherent vowel in all these scripts.&lt;ref name=&quot;World 408&quot; /&gt; Other similarities include the diacritic for {{angle bracket|ai}}, which resembles a doubled {{angle bracket|e}} in all scripts and the diacritic for {{angle bracket|au}} which is composed of preceding {{angle bracket|e}} and following {{angle bracket|·∏∑}}.

{| class=&quot;wikitable&quot;
|-
! Script !! {{angle bracket|e}} !! {{angle bracket|ai}}
!{{angle bracket|au}}
|-
| Sinhala || ‡∑ô || ‡∑õ
|‡∑û
|-
| [[Malayalam alphabet|Malayalam]] || ‡µÜ || ‡µà
|‡µó
|-
| [[Tamil alphabet|Tamil]] || ‡ØÜ || ‡Øà
|‡Øå
|-
| [[Bengali alphabet|Bengali]] || ‡ßá || ‡ßà
|‡ßå
|-
| [[Devanagari alphabet|DƒìvanƒÅgarƒ´]] || ‡•á || ‡•à
|‡•å
|}

Likewise, the combination of the diacritics for {{angle bracket|e}} and {{angle bracket|ƒÅ}} yields {{angle bracket|o}} in all these scripts.
